author's, author is
'em, them
they're, they are
don't, do not
part's, part is
throughout's, throughout is
it's, it is
you're, you are
that's, that is
Vi's, Vi is
isn't, is not
I'd, I had
here's, here has
Every single one either a commonly accepted standard english contraction, or a contraction for the previously stated purpose of sentence flow that makes sense in the context of where it was in the sentence.
My punctuation is fine, thank you very much. Probably one of a handful of anons who actually go out of their way to punctuate properly on that note.
If I were writing a college paper or the like, I may be more inclined to write in a fashion that looses flow and readability for hard conformity to the english language, but I'm posting in a fap thread on 4chan, the fact I'm even remotely writing in english that's not a step or two above text and/or l33t speak's half a miracle to anyone who bothere's to read it.

>People think that when they talk about immortality, they talk about immortality in the most pejorative terms. A guy who lives 180 years or 1000 years, that's immortality? It isn't. You have to go through your check list, right? One of them, it says: dying. Why should one of them be more important than the rest? The moment it ceases to be important—your death, not other people's death; I really have a tough time with somebody dying because of the love I feel for them—but in my personal life dying is as unimportant as changing my shoes and my socks or [brushing] my teeth. It's just another thing I have to do. It's part of the laundry list. So at that moment you become somewhat immortal, which means you're immune to death.

>That is in Pan's Labyrinth actually. If people watch it carefully, the precise wording of the faun's words to the girl is: "You have to pass three tests before the full moon shines in the sky. We have to make sure that your spirit is intact and not become mortal." That's the real purpose of the tests. It's not if she gets the dagger and she gets the key, those are the mechanics of the test, mechanics which she can then proceed to fault. She can flunk the tests. The mechanics of the test she succeeds in. She believes in herself. She does what she thinks is right. She fucks up here and there but—when the real test come, when she is cornered with no other options but to either kill or give her own life—she chooses to put her own life at risk rather than the kid's. It's not that hmofa avoids sparkledogism specifically, it's more the dearth of subscription to popularized archetypes, like you pointed out re: Hlad's sharkgril. For example, early hmofa had its dommy, punk-goth hyena girls, but for the most part, really fell over heels for the demure, abused schoolgirl. Shark's Anya (raptor girl) is an accountant with a taste for metal that she doesn't express over her social clumsiness and need and intimacy. I'm not a fan of Chapel's Mara for the simple reason that I can't stand dog hybrids (or any hybrid), but she's another shark girl that bucks the trend, being herself a mousy (though situationally bumptious) and studious bookworm. Coughing's Teth'ra bucks the dommy jackal trend despite her being a big girl and, in that sense, bucking another stereotype; she's also awkward and endearing in person. Despite her significant advantages, and being a literal (sic) war hound, she has needs that she has trouble requiting, and through interaction with other characters like Tom, her personal shortcomings are exhibited.

Preferential shit. See, a 90s cartoon conceptualized the idea. Shark girls took off decades later when there was enough art and interest to correlate with a time of the year to draw fucktons of shark girls (Shark Week).
